==English==
===Etymology===
{{L.}} From ''frater'': brother + ''caedere'': to kill.
===Noun===
'''fratricide'''
#The [[killing]] of one's [[brother]] (or [[sister]]).
#A person who [[commit]]s this [[crime]].
#*'''1936''': H A L Fisher: A History of Europe: Edward Arnold Publishers P.376.
::"The conversion of Russia to Christianity was effected, it would seem by a monster of cruelty and lust. That Vladimir (980 - 1015) was a '''fratricide''', who mantained 3,500 concubines, has not prevented his canonization as a saint."
